data.text:
The issue is that `focusable.length - 1` could result in accessing an undefined element if the query returns a NodeList that TypeScript doesn't know is non-empty. Actually, there's a guard `if (focusable.length === 0) return;` so after that, `focusable[focusable.length - 1]` should be defined. But TypeScript's type narrowing for `NodeListOf` might not work well with `querySelectorAll`.

The fix is to use `focusable.item(focusable.length - 1)` or to cast it. Actually, the simplest fix is to use non-null assertion or to check that `last` is defined before calling `.focus()`.

Let me add a guard:
```tsx
const last = focusable[focusable.length - 1];
if (event.shiftKey) {
  if (document.activeElement === first) {
    event.preventDefault();
    last?.focus();
  }
} else {
  if (document.activeElement === last) {
    event.preventDefault();
    first.focus();
  }
}
```

Or I can use `focusable.item(focusable.length - 1)` which returns `HTMLElement | null`.

